{"cursor":"16531","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\ns in an aqueous solution.]]\n\n\nA 'liposome' is an artificially-prepared vesicle composed of a lipid bilayer.\nThe liposome can be used as a vehicle for administration of nutrients and\npharmaceutical drugs. [http://users.rcn.com/jkimball.ma.ultranet/BiologyPag-\nes/C/CellMembranes.html Kimball's Biology Pages,] \"Cell Membranes.\"\nLiposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes (such as by\nsonication).\n\nLiposomes are composed of natural soya or egg Phosphatidylcholine enriched\nphospholipids like LECIVA-S90, LIPOVA-E120 etc. and may also contain mixed lipid\nchains with surfactant properties (e.g., egg phosphatidylethanolamine). A\nliposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy\ntissue. Torchilin, V.P. (2006). Advanced Drug Delivery Reviews. 20\n\nThe major types of liposomes are the 'multilamellar vesicle' ('MLV'), the 'small\nunilamellar vesicle' ('SUV'), the 'large unilamellar vesicle' ('LUV'), and the\n'cochleate vesicle'. [http://www.twst.com/notes/articles/wac609.html\nExplanation on twst.com commercial page, cf. also Int.Patent PCT/US2008/074543\non p.4, section 0014]\n\nLiposomes should not be confused with micelles and reverse micelles composed of\nmonolayers. Stryer S. (1981)\nBiochemistry, 213\n","linknr":495,"url":"liposomes","recorded":1362898634,"links":50,"instances":["biology_and_chemistry","physics","cell_biology","food"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Membrane biology","Drug delivery devices","Dosage forms"],"headings":["Discovery","Mechanism","Liposomes in Dietary & Nutritional Supplements","Manufacturing","Prospect","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Liposome_scheme-en.svg/250px-Liposome_scheme-en.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-